##On the 10th, the people of Wuhan saved themselves

MICRO-SIGNAL YITIAOTV

Feature description, a short original video every day, every day to tell a moving story, every day selected human beauty, every day to live a better life with me.

Data Source: real-time tracking of new crown pneumonia in tencent

As of 7 a.m. on 3 February,

There were 16,615 confirmed cases of NCP in China,

5,142 confirmed cases in Wuhan.

According to the press conference on the epidemic situation in Hubei Province on January 31,

As at 2400 hours on 30th,

There are more than 60,000 medical workers in Wuhan

There are 42 medical teams supporting Wuhan, with 4,599 medical staff.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Volunteer driver of Wuhan 123 motorcade

After the city was closed, the transportation system in Wuhan was shut down,

Many health care workers can only walk or cycle to work,

The supply of prevention and control materials for front-line medical care is also very tight,

Could not bear to see the hardships of the anti-epidemic fighters,

The most ordinary citizen in the city is on the move.

Ordinary workers, students, white-collar workers, small businesses,

Under the pressure of the plague, he volunteered to be a team volunteer:

Free Transport of medical staff to and from work;

Or trying to pull in scarce supplies,

To first-line hospitals, communities.

Supplies delivered by he Jinglin, a volunteer with the Wuhan Qingshan District, Wuhan motorcade

The volunteers'protective gear is very basic,

Sometimes I get busy, working from morning till night,

No one was paid a penny.

A reader in Wuhan learned about these people,

We first contacted Captain Huang Xiaomin of the Wuhan 123 motorcade,

And the Wuhan Qingshan District, Wuhan volunteer motorcade,

They recommended the impressed volunteers around them,

"There's a kid from the'90s who's everywhere. "

"You must get a good interview with Wu,

I've only known him for a few days, but I really admire him..."

It is very difficult to interview these volunteers,

Because they're on the road most of the time,

The end of the day is usually at night, sometimes with a phone interview,

They said apologetically,

To pick up the paramedics or drop off supplies again.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
"refueling in Wuhan" by team volunteers

One of the team's volunteers said,

"In the evening I received a grandfather,

At 72, the army doctor returned to the Community Hospital,

He walked across the river for two hours in the morning to go to work.

He said he was very confident in winning the battle,

He's not afraid. So I'm not afraid.

On my way home, I saw the lights on. Go, Wuhan."

By Ni Jianjia

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Team Captain Huang Xiaomin picked up a nurse who had just finished a 24-hour shift

"We transport about 200 people to and from work every day. "

Huang Xiaomin, 38

Occupation: Commercial Real Estate, marketing

Epidemic Period: Wuhan "123 Rescue Convoy" captain

On January 23rd, after the city of Wuhan was shut down, I assembled a 123 rescue convoy. Because the only thing I can do now is drive the paramedics to and from work.

From the company to my home, will pass 4 hospitals, a few days before the closure of the city, I often see some medical staff after the night shift to stop the car is very difficult. And I thought, you know, I could do it.

Written by Huang Xiaomin on January 23

On the 23rd, Wuhan's transportation system was shut down, and I quickly figured out how to get them to work? That night on Wechat set up a "Wuhan Doctor Travel Mutual Help Group" , looking for colleagues and students to do driver volunteers, and then more and more strangers to join.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The girl volunteer driver from the 123rd

There are now more than 90 drivers in the fleet, with the youngest being a man born in 1997 and one in 10 being women. We shuttle about 200 doctors and nurses to and from work every day.

Named "123 motorcade" because of the date of the siege and because "1,2,3! " Is a quick signal to start. We later found that it rhymes with "Guan de Kuan, " Or "Guan de Kuan, " in Wuhan.

On the night of the 23rd I took a job, first without a hat and goggles, then with a swimming cap and goggles, and then a young nurse who gave me a splash mask. Fortunately, I have more than 1,000 friends on Wechat. After my friends sent me a message, the message went out. Volunteers from all over the country sent me some protective clothing, face masks, and a small convenience store in Wuhan. They got the 84 disinfectant, saved two cases just for us. We can say that "the beginning of a car, equipment depends on picking up. "

We each took 3-5 jobs a day, I took 10 jobs a day at the most, went out at 6:00 in the morning and came home at 7:00 at night. Generally take some dry food in the car to eat, do not dare to drink water, go to the toilet is very inconvenient.

A 62-year-old doctor who was rehired told me that he had to cycle to work for two hours and 15 minutes before our team picked him up.

Most of the nurses were post-'95 kids, a 1996 ICU nurse who got off the night shift at 7:00 in the morning and fell asleep in my car, luckily I knew where she lived.

A doctor asked us to pick up his father, who was also a doctor, and they were going to different hospitals, and he couldn't take care of him at work.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
WECHAT group refuses to accept payment

For protection, we asked the paramedics to talk to the driver as little as possible, and we were strangers and it was always quiet on the bus. I'll talk to them at the Red Light. I asked a nurse what she wanted to do when the outbreak was over? She said she wanted a good drink of water and 48 hours of sleep.

A young Concorde nurse, who was not in the respiratory or infectious diseases department, said she would volunteer to go to the front when Vulcan and thor hospitals were built.

When many doctors and nurses get off the bus, they just drop 100 yuan in cash or send red envelopes on Wechat. We don't accept them. Sometimes I even give them red envelopes.

My wife took her 1-year-old son home to yellowstone for the New Year before she closed the city. When I told her I wanted to be a team on Wechat, she was silent for a few minutes. Then I told her about the condition of the medical staff, working all night and waiting for the bus, and the big hospital has a bus, the Community Health Service Center does not... then she gave me back: You Go, protect yourself.

Team 123 volunteers

Some drivers are out of the wife, my classmates let me send friends circle do not mention him, he is to tell his wife is out playing Mahjong, Mahjong partners are very healthy, or go fishing.

Yesterday there was a single, is from Wuhan Eight Hospital to Jiangxia District, the entire journey 30 km, just saw me worried about this single no answer, but soon a driver said: No one, I go!

In addition to the drivers, our group has 20 support volunteers, who gather information on the medical staff and the drivers'movements every day, coordinate supplies, and find ways to bring in donated supplies, often working from early morning until 1 or 2 am.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The volunteer holds the motorcade logo

I live with my parents now, my home is a transit point, we have received donations of 300 masks, 300 protective clothing, but online donations of 1,000 goggles are still stuck in the road, I am the distribution of supplies to volunteers, check their 3 cards 1 single (ID, driver's license, driving license, insurance policy) , on the issue of supplies. Everyone wore masks and didn't recognize each other. Everyone spoke little but moved quickly.

Friends also designed the team logo for the team, logistics volunteers printed, we go to separate, posted in the car windshield under the traffic police see our logo, will let.

There are more stories around us. There is a newly married couple. The newly decorated wedding room is in the community near Houhu Central Hospital. They give the new room to the medical staff free of charge, and they refuse to accept even a deposit, i don't even think I can do that.

Huang Xiaomin's circle of friends

In order to ventilate, our windows are always open. Wuhan is very cold in the early morning, often 1 C below zero, and drivers wear protective clothing and gloves, so they sweat easily, so 20% of our drivers now have cold symptoms, i started coughing, too.

On the 28th, during the outbreak period, 800 new cases were confirmed in Wuhan. I felt extremely stressed and cried twice because I initiated the motorcade, but I could not take responsibility for the lives of the volunteers. So I'm going to write an initiative, and we're going to stop taking orders from January 29th, when we can get protective clothing, en14126type4 and above, and N95 masks, and if the city still needs us, we'll keep picking up and dropping off paramedics.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
To deliver supplies to the hospital

But after the 29th, our convoy did not stop, mainly to help transport supplies to the front line. I also managed to buy some through a friend. Supplies were so tight, I sent over all the non-medical goggles, and the doctor texted that even a piece of glass was needed.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Wuhan doctors and nurses are making their own protective masks

At 4:00 p.m. on January 30th, I received 10 cases of alcohol, and after I posted on my facebook page, I was approached by a lot of doctors and nurses, all of whom said they needed it. I was also approached by a nurse from the eight hospitals. I asked you in a strange way if the eight hospitals are not mainly engaged in the Department of Anus and intestine? He said that they are now also designated hospitals. Then they sent a picture of their doctor doing it himself, using the folder as a protective mask. I couldn't hold it in my mind when I saw the picture, and I cried.

I was under a great deal of pressure, on the one hand, for fear that the volunteers would get sick, for fear that my family would get sick, and on the other hand, for fear that medical resources would not be enough.

When this epidemic is over, I want nothing more than to see my family, give them hugs and kisses.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
"The first thing I do when I open my eyes,

Thinking about where to get supplies."

Wu Yaoguang, 33

Occupation: Tattoo artist

EPIDEMIC PERIOD: raising and transporting materials for Wuhan

I am the president of the Hubei Branch of the Chinese Tattoo Association, a native of Shaanxi, married to a Wuhan daughter-in-law, living in Wuhan for many years, usually open a tattoo studio.

Tattoo artist career is embarrassing, many people think it is undesirable elements, so after the closure of the city, "Qingshan District, Wuhan Epidemic Prevention and Control Volunteer Team" to accept my application to join, I am quite happy.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Wu Yaoguang volunteers for Qingshan District, Wuhan outbreak prevention and control

On January 25, with the support of Tian You, the President of the Chinese Tattoo Association, I raised funds from Tattoo artists all over the country, raising 77,250 yuan for the first time, i gave $10,000 of my own. All this money was used to buy scarce supplies.

There are several main channels for buying supplies, and it's a good thing that most of them have been taken over by the government, to some of the mask factories around Wuhan. And then there's the large volunteer group of supplies, where the manufacturers send in their supplies and certificates, and the doctors are in the group, and they look at it and say it's ready to use, and we buy it and ship it to them. Another is to find a second-hand dealer who has stockpiled supplies.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Lunch on the way to transport supplies

After the purchase of supplies, the first time sent to the various departments of the hospital in need. Some supplies were not up to medical standards, so we donated to communities, volunteers, front-line journalists, police brigades and so on.

For example, N95 masks and goggles were sent to the Wuchang Branch of the Wuhan Public Security Bureau, because the branch police were to be stationed at the seven hospitals in Wuhan. All they had was some surgical masks, and the suits were rotated, which wasn't enough, and I knew that some of them were home quarantined with suspected infections.

Late at night to help carry masks to south-central hospital

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The next morning, we set out to stock up on disinfectant

On the evening of the 31st, I and other volunteers went to various mask manufacturers and haggled over the price. The medical masks cost 1.80 yuan each. We finally got the goods in the early morning of February 1st, at 2:40 am, I sent 40,000 masks to Wuhan Zhongnan Hospital. I also bought tens of thousands of masks which cost 1.25 yuan each, which can be given to non-frontline personnel.

That night I went home to find a sofa and lay down. I slept for three hours. On the morning of February 1, I went to buy Xiantao again. I bought 500 catties of alcohol and 50 catties of disinfectant. I sent 15 catties of alcohol and 20 catties of disinfectant to Wuhan 161 hospital, to three hospitals, golden pond hospital... and went to the various community distribution, by now (the interview is on February 1 at 9:00 p.m.) has been all empty.

My biggest feeling is that sending stuff to every hospital is a lifesaver for them. The doctors were kind to me, too, filling me with vials of disinfectant, only allowing me to stand outside the gate and wait for them to come and get it.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Wu Yaoguang and the leadership of the medical team to discuss material procurement

Because I am a native of Shaanxi Province, I was very excited to see the Shaanxi medical team coming. On the 29th, I went to their hotel to see if there was anything I could do. Even though I was staying in the hotel, there were still some places where I could not take care of my daily necessities, i consulted with the medical team leaders to see what they lacked, and purchased laundry detergent, pots, eyedrops and other items to send them.

These days it is usually 4:00 in the morning before going to bed, to send a list of materials, wake up at 7 or 8 in the morning to start looking for supplies, at noon to buy supplies, contact the hospital, the community to start sending.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
In fact, I do not have a driver's license, all the way is the team of volunteers with me to transport, these Wuhan locals let me very touched, can see Wuhan very united side. I Open my eyes every morning first thing, is to think today where to buy supplies, and then send which hospitals, dream to buy a mask is to wake up to laugh.

Right now, our supply truck is parked on the side of the road, and we're taking a break when you call. But that's all for now. The crowd says there's 30 pounds of alcohol, and we need to get out there and get it.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Send Goggles to hospital (second left is Li Feng, third left is Wu Yaoguang)

"I helped Wu drive supplies,

The doctor was treated like a baby."

Li Feng, 27

Occupation: self-employed, opened in Wuhan Purple Swallow Chicken Franchise Shop

During the outbreak: volunteer drivers

Before the outbreak, I was traveling because I didn't know what was going on. I broke my right rib while skiing in Shennongjia, Hubei Province on January 19. When I returned to Wuhan on the 21st, I saw the news and started reporting, so I thought I'd do something about it.

After closing down the city, a friend who drives a Didi private car said the government would give every large community 2-3 cars to be drivers for 800 yuan a day and asked me if I wanted to go. But I do not want to do this, I joined two groups of volunteers, one is dedicated to transport medical staff, one is and old Wu (Wu Yaoguang) transport supplies.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Volunteer Li Feng

Because the RIB fracture has not been repaired, I feel pain after driving for a long time, so I can not run outside Wuhan, nor can I carry heavy loads, I can only do more in the urban area of Wuhan.

Materials are really in short supply. On the afternoon of January 30, Lao Wu and I sent 15 goggles to the Qingshan Children's hospital, because there were a group of doctors going to the front line. The doctors were so happy to see us all as babies, and asked us to find some more alcohol.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Wuhan residents also volunteered to cut hair for medical staff

About a quarter of the 357 people who volunteer to pick up and drop off patients are drivers, and the rest are health care workers, who send requests to the group, but the number of active drivers is probably only five or six, it's even slower if it's a long drive.

On January 28, I went to Jiangxia District to pick up a young nurse from the hospital in Qingshan District, Wuhan, 60 kilometers back and forth, and after a few minutes of no response to an appointment, I picked her up. She was going home to get some supplies, because the hospital had helped them find a hotel.

On January 29th, a 30-year-old nurse from the fever clinic came home, and she told me to wait downstairs. She had to pick up something and go to the hospital. She and her daughter could not see each other at home because of self-isolation.

Doctors and nurses don't have time for themselves, and they fall asleep right after they get in the car.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Li Feng is drying his equipment

In the beginning, the only protection was the three N95 masks I got from my friends. Each one was sterilized and reused for three days. Today, I took down the last mask. After sending a friend's message, someone offered me another one, and I could use it for another three days. Old Wu and I bought protective clothing because of the small number of the hospital, I did not give up A.

I was inside the home is self-isolation, go home to sterilize the body first, mother cooked a good meal, and when they eat good back to the room, I take disposable chopsticks out to pick up food, back to their room to eat.

When I'm driving, I'm mostly thinking about where I'm going next, preferably all the time. It cured my body clock, too. I usually sleep past 10:00, then go to my shop, but lately I've been up since 6:00.

It's 9:30 at night, so that's it. I've got two more appointments to make, one at 10:00, one at 12:00, and one at 6:00 in the morning in Hankou. It's a long drive.

Qingshan District, Wuhan Team Volunteer Lee yiu-sing

"The other volunteers looked at me as if I were a child,

Just ask me how old I am, and I'll say'99."

Lee Yiu Sing, 21

Occupation: University student in Wuhan

During the outbreak: Qingshan District, Wuhan team volunteers

My family in Wuhan Qingshan District, Wuhan, also in Wuhan University, six months ago to get a driver's license. When I saw that the Qingshan District, Wuhan Youth League Committee was organizing volunteers, I signed up for a free ride. Mom and dad are always worried, before going out, mom will see me put on a mask, give me spray alcohol.

My father, a veteran with a badly needed A2 driver's license, was eager to attend, but he had a cold and was quarantined at home.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Photo taken by Lee Yiu sing outside car window

Remember January 25 received the first single, is a general hospital in Wuhan Iron and steel on duty nurse, 9 pm under a light rain, she said I am glad to come, otherwise she would have to walk in the rain on the road to see if there is a car.

I picked up a 97-year-old nurse at 7:00 in the morning. She got out of the car and sent me a message saying, "I really want to buy you breakfast, but I don't want to waste your time. " This simple communication made me feel very warm.

One of the busiest days was a trip to a warehouse in Caidian District to pick up supplies, a thousand boxes of water, masks and gloves, etc. . While carrying the supplies, other volunteers looked at me and asked me, like a child, how old I was. I said I was born in'99.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A female doctor in her 40s, she commutes to work by bike for 40 minutes after the city is closed. When I picked her up, she specially brought alcohol, mask, even flowers qingwen capsule to me. When my mother, roommate, in college, developed symptoms of a suspected infection and was quarantined at home but couldn't get any sanitizers, I thought of the woman doctor, who informed us and gave us alcohol from her home.

Of Lee and his college roommate, separately calling Wuhan Hospital

On January 27, roommate's mother got worse. Roommate bought an oxygen machine, and his mother had to breathe on oxygen, constantly, with Black Lips. On January 29, they were notified by the community office to do a nucleic acid test at Hanyang hospital, the nurse told her that she would get the results in six hours, but she did not receive any notification and was never diagnosed.

Roommate's mother went into a coma on the 30th and was rushed to Hanyang Hospital. She was stable but was told she could not be hospitalized.

He and his father went to more than 10 hospitals, none of which were able to handle hospitalization, and now both he and his father are showing signs of infection, because they have a 14 year old sister at home, and neither he nor his father dare come home and sleep in the car. At two or three in the morning on January 31st, my roommate and I separately called every hospital in Wuhan, to no avail.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
My roommate's situation in Wuhan is not unique, there are a lot of special.

On the way to the hospital, my car has been cycling Leslie Cheung's Song "Synchronous Winter" , "a person with an umbrella, the wind will be particularly strong, synchronous winter, together against the cold wind... through the cold winter, embrace success, another day to think of this is not cold. "

I hope it's like the end of the song, "Don't be sad to say. "

Special thanks: He Jinglin, a volunteer of the Wuhan Qingshan District, Wuhan team, for his help in the interview

The Vulcan Mountain Hospital is listed on the Internet

The official opening of Wuhan's COVID-19 on Feb. 2, and the start of treatment today, marks a new phase in the fight against the epidemic.

In the more than ten days of the city closure in Wuhan, ordinary citizens on the human nature of the light people moved, they were devastated by life and not servile, as frustrated and efforts to shine.

One stands firmly with the rest of us, witnessing the greatness of these ordinary people, and continuing to record the faint, warm light of the epidemic.

We look forward to the spring of 2020, the day when the epidemic is fully over.
